musical_form.description: The Saffron Lyric is a form of music used for entertainment originating in The Flute of Wheels. The form guides musicians during improvised performances. The music is played on a macame. The entire performance is at a hurried pace. The melody has short phrases throughout the form. It is performed without preference for a scale and in the ada rhythm. Throughout, when possible, performers are to modulate frequently. [B]The macame always does the main melody, should sparkle and is to start loud then be immediately soft. [B]The Saffron Lyric has a well-defined multi-passage structure: a verse and a brief chorus all repeated up to two times and a finale. [B]In the verse, the macame ranges from the resonant low register to the heavy middle register. Only one pitch is ever played at a time in this passage. [B]In the chorus, the macame covers its entire range from the resonant low register to the sweet high register. Chords are packed close together in dense clusters in this passage. [B]In the finale, the macame covers its entire range from the resonant low register to the sweet high register. This passage is richly layered with full chords making use of the available range. [B]The ada rhythm is made from two patterns: the cede and the datome. The patterns are to be played over the same period of time, concluding together regardless of beat number. [B]The cede rhythm is a single line with thirty-two beats divided into four bars in a 8-8-8-8 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - X - - - x x x | x X x x x x x x | - x x X - x x - | - x - - - - - - | [B]where X marks an accented beat, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The datome rhythm is a single line with seven beats. The beats are named lari (spoken la), aratha (ar), imeri (im), thna (th), fidale (fi), tarathe (ta) and cuthefi (cu). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - x x - - - - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar.

The Sister of Poets is a form of music used during marches and military engagements originating in The Lone Growls. Throughout, when possible, composers and performers are to play rapid runs. [B]Each singer always does the main melody, should be passionate and uses mordents. The voice stays in the high register. [B]The Sister of Poets has a simple structure: a passage. [B]The simple passage accelerates as it proceeds, and it is to be soft. [B]Scales are constructed from twelve notes spaced evenly throughout the octave. The tonic note is a fixed tone passed from teacher to student. Preferred notes in the fundamental scale are named. The names are thna (spoken th, 7th) and arazi (ar, 11th). [B]The imeri hexatonic scale is thought of as joined chords spanning a perfect fifth and a perfect fourth. These chords are named eyo and fela. [B]The eyo tetrachord is the 1st, the 3rd, the 5th and the 8th degrees of the semitone octave scale. [B]The fela tetrachord is the 8th, the 10th, the 11th and the 13th (completing the octave) degrees of the semitone octave scale. [B]The masa rhythm is made from two patterns: the le and the cenopu. The patterns are to be played over the same period of time, concluding together regardless of beat number. [B]The le rhythm is a single line with seven beats. The beats are named atha (spoken ath), alo (al), avea (av), mafina (ma), pama (pa), bulifo (bu) and ada (ad). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| X'- x - - - x | [B]where X marks an accented beat, ' marks a beat as late, x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The cenopu rhythm is a single line with three beats. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x X x | [B]where X marks an accented beat, x is a beat and | indicates a bar.
